# Cuescore manual

**NOTE:** The platform is continually under development, which means the Manual will not always be 100% up to date.

This document has been in the planning for a long time and we are sorry for keeping you waiting.

We’ll do our best to keep the document updated as new functionality is added or changes are done.

Since the launch in 2015/16 the platform has grown big and a lot of functionality has been added. We have tried to cover it, but there are probably still some topics missing.

# 1\. Homepage and Pro dashboard {#1.-homepage-and-pro-dashboard}

If you have a Cuescore profile you would normally end up on your homepage. If not, you can click the Cuescore Icon.

**Before you do anything else, click the “Edit” symbol beside your picture and update your Country, Nationality and Timezone to make sure things are displayed correctly on the site.**

## Homepage {#homepage}

![][image1]  
On the homepage the default view is showing your activity, tournaments you follow and your stats.  
You can navigate between tabs (Overview, Tournaments, Challenges and Teams) to see your activity.

### Manager \- discontinued {#manager---discontinued}

## Pro Dashboard {#pro-dashboard}

The Dashboard is available from the Dashboard icon in the upper, left corner.

Click it and you get access to navigate to your Pro Dashboard(s). If you have access to multiple Pro accounts you will get a dropdown list where you can select.

To switch back to your homepage, click the Cuescore Icon in the upper, left corner.

The general idea is that you are logged in as yourself and can switch to the role as an administrator of the Pro account. When you go to the Pro dashboard, you get full access to its functionality.

# 2\. A look at the Pro Dashboard {#2.-a-look-at-the-pro-dashboard}

This is where you find all the tools that we hope will make your life a bit easier as tournament manager or if you have some other role in your club/organization.

![][image2]

Note that the mobile view has a different layout due to size of the screen.

## Profile link {#profile-link}

This is a link to your clubs/organizations “PRO page” where everything past, present and future happenings are displayed and available to everyone visiting Cuescore.  
E.g Upcoming tournaments, news, tournament calendar, ranking and so on….

Encourage the participants in your tournaments to follow the page, and they will get a notification when you publish a new tournament, news and so on.

## Dashboard Menu {#dashboard-menu}

The two other sections are actually the same, with the one to the right being the visible one when you are on a mobile device.

Short description of the Menu elements:

###  Profile (Pro Page visible for visitors to Cuescore) {#profile-(pro-page-visible-for-visitors-to-cuescore)}

This is where you update/add logo and Pro header picture, contact information, season, country and other stuff for your Pro account. It will be visible on your Pro page “About” section”.

Make sure you update info in this section.

### Tournaments {#tournaments}

List of all tournaments organized by your Pro account. Default listing is “Active/Finished” and there is a quick filter for upcoming.  
You also have other filters available. **NOTE\!** If you have drafted a tournament you will have to change the “Status” filter to see it.

“Create new” \- Click the button if you want to create a new tournament.

**Copy tournament**  
If you organize a weekly tournament, you might save some time by copying the basic setup.  
Press the “Copy” icon and you will get the same settings.

You are given the option to copy settings and include the participants, in case of recurring events.  
   
(Remember to change the name and check the dates.)

### Point systems {#point-systems}

If you already have a point system added, it will be listed here.

This is also where you create your own point systems for use in rankings, click “Create”.

Define the points for each position in the result table. Note that you only have to define points for the positions in the result table. E.g in the example below there are two 3rd places and then the next is 5th place.  
1 \- 100 pts  
2 \- 90 pts  
3 \- 80 pts  
5 \- 70 pts  
9 \- 60 pts ………..and so on.

### Rankings {#rankings}

This page lists all your rankings and gives you edit access, e.g if you want to add new tournaments to the ranking list.

“New ranking” button creates a new ranking list.

### Handicaps {#handicaps}

Create and/or manage HCP lists you have for your events.

Note that this is not a HCP system. This is a way to show a player's HCP beside his name in the bracket and refer to your “HCP system”. The HCP can be a number/letter or both (1, A, A+ ….)

### Players(and creation of player profiles) {#players(and-creation-of-player-profiles)}

A tool to keep track of your organizations/clubs members.  
A lot of clubs/organizations need to report activity and members to get funding. Here you find tools  to keep track of your members, with key information, and the possibility to keep track of yearly membership fees (if relevant).

**Adding existing profiles to your organization/club**

![][image3]

Simply press the “Add” button and search for the player's name.  
If he/she has a profile, add it and fill in the extra information you need.

NOTE \- the search field you see in the picture above will search in your member list. To add a new member to the list, you need to press “Add” and then search.

**Create new profile**  
If you want to add a player that has no profile, you should create a public profile for him/her. (best option is to ask the player to create their profile of course)  
Click the “Add” button and do a search for the name. If you get no result, use the link below the search field to create a public profile. See picture below.

![][image4]

\*\*\* Note that it’s also possible to create player profiles from the tournament page from the “Add players” button.

### Teams (New\!) {#teams-(new!)}

As a lot of league managers do the whole setup of teams, we have recently added functionality to create teams from the dashboard. This way any other admin of the Pro account always has access to edit teams.

An important improvement is that you always have access to Scoreboard codes and Stream overlay from your venue list, so that you can set up your tablets without planning a tournament.

Click the “Arrow down” beside the name of the venue and you get all tables listed, including “Code”.  
This code is entered on the tablet on the following link:  [https://cuescore.com/scoreboard/](https://cuescore.com/scoreboard/)

# 3\. Share access {#3.-share-access}

In Cuescore you have the option to share edit access with others to a number of objects. An object is typically a tournament, team, PRO account or ranking list.  
How to share access?  
Simply go to the page in question, e.g a tournament you have created, and press the “Share” button located close to the top right on the page. As you already have edit access, you will see a list of those who have access to edit the page.  
Grant access to others by searching their name and adding them. They will be notified by email (including a link to the tournament). In the list you can also remove the access by pressing the (X) besides the name.

![][image5]

## PRO account access {#pro-account-access}

To share full access to your Cuescore PRO, go to the public PRO home page and press the Share link. This share option is usually used when you want to give others in the club access to create official club tournaments and general access to the functionality.  
In many cases you just want to share access to a tournament manager or someone helping to organize an event. If so, sharing access to the tournament only might be a good option.

**NOTE:** By adding a person as Tournament manager in Cuescore, you only inform that he/she is the tournament manager and show the contact details. You do not share Edit access with the person.

# 4\. Venues {#4.-venues}

To take full advantage of Cuescore and its live score functionality, you should create your venue (where you host your tournaments) and add its tables.

When you create a new venue (Press the Create button on the Venue page) you get the option to add contact information, tables, images and share access to other Pro accounts.  
Behind the venue's name you find the link to the public venue page.

![][image6]

**Add tables**  
Press the “Billiard tables” tab and add tables. Note that you have a copy function to make it easier to add multiple tables of the same type. On this page you always have the tablet codes available and the link to the stream overlay for each table.  
![][image7]

Be sure to enter the correct “Branch” for each table. This information is used to match available tables for a tournament with the same branch.

# 5\. Tournaments, leagues/competitions {#5.-tournaments,-leagues/competitions}

Cuescore supports all the most used formats, including tournaments, leagues, group play/round robin and combinations.

In the Pro dashboard, you find all your events in the “Tournament” section and this is also where you go to create new events.  
What you actually do when you click “Create new” is to create an “object”. When the object is created you can later define the type/format in the settings. The format is what decides if it’s a tournament, league or whatever. Tournament settings are covered more in dept as a separate chapter.

The league format is probably best explained like this:  
1 (one) group of players, where every player meets once, twice or more times. Usually over a period of several weeks.

\*\*\* Notice that there are big variations in the naming of formats across borders. What we have named League in the formats section is the same as others refer to as Competition. What we call Tournament, others have referred to as Competition when contacting support.

#  6\. Format / bracket / flowchart \- RR/SE/DE {#6.-format-/-bracket-/-flowchart---rr/se/de}

A key element to managing tournaments (also in Cuescore) is to understand the different types of formats.  
CueScore has a long list of brackets available and understanding our naming convention is quite important. for both experienced and rookie tournament managers. 

What type of Format to use depends on factors like time available, number of participants and number of tables available. A tournament/competition lasting more than a week is very often run as a league, where players or teams meet to play a weekly match.

If the tournament is finished within a couple of days, the most used Formats are the Single Elimination, Double Elimination, a mix of these two or Round Robin.

Below you will find more details on our naming convention and the different types of brackets.

## Formats {#formats}

### Single Elimination (SE) {#single-elimination-(se)}

This is the easiest format available. The participants are drawn into the bracket and from there, if you lose a match you are out of the tournament. If you win, you go on to the next round until there's only one left.

The number of rounds in a bracket depends on how many players you have. Single elimination brackets naturally grow by the power of 2\. So you have bracket sizes from 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, etc.

*Single Elimination is a very effective bracket to use, especially if you have little time, a lot of players or a limited number of tables available. On the negative side, the players get only one chance. Lose one match and you are out.*

### Double Elimination (DE), incl. mixed DE-\>SE {#double-elimination-(de),-incl.-mixed-de->se}

Double Elimination means that any player will get a second chance and have to lose two matches before he/she is out of the tournament. If a player loses one match, he is transferred over to the "loser-side" of the bracket, and continue to play there until he loses a second match or reach either the final, or the final stage of the tournament (mixed DE-SE).

The Double Elimination brackets in Cuescore are described by two numbers. The first number tells you how many players there can be in total. The second number tells you how many players advance to the single elimination stage. This number can be 2 at the lowest, which means it's a Double Elimination all the way to the final (winner on the loser side meets the winner of the winners-side of the bracket). The single elimination stage grows by the number of two.

Bracket size 64-16 has a maximum number of 64 players, with Single Elimination stage when there are 16 players left. If you lose a match in the SE stage, you are out, even if this is the first match you lose.

*The Double Elimination brackets require more time, as more matches are played. The players like it, as they know they can still advance after an early loss.*

### Round-Robin (RR) {#round-robin-(rr)}

Round Robin is a format where every player meets all other players once. The RR brackets can consist of more than one group. The brackets are typically named RR G1, where the G stands for Group and the number next to it tells you how many groups in the schema.

Round Robin is often used in combination with a Single Elimination for the final stages. In Cuescore this is indicated by the last letter/number combination in the name (e.g. RR G2 **SE4**). The example means that it's a Round Robin with two groups. Four players (the two best from each group) will advance to the Single Elimination part of the bracket.

*Round Robin is a popular format, as each player gets to play many matches. Most suited when there is a low number of players participating.*

### League {#league}

League is the same as a Round-Robin, but with only one group.

It is intended for single and team league play, hence the name, The number indicates how many times the players/teams should meet. It goes from one to eight. In team play you often meet twice, once at home venue and once at the opponent's home venue. The draw for this setup is carefully made to make sure participants get an equal amount of home and away games. The league brackets do not have a single elimination stage afterwards.

In Cuescore \- League x 1 \= every player meets once, League x 2 \= every player meets twice…..

*As the name indicates.....used for league play.*

### Single Elimination Qualifier / Double Elimination Qualifier {#single-elimination-qualifier-/-double-elimination-qualifier}

Sometimes you want to "split" a big tournament into qualifiers and a final, to make it more manageable. For this we have the Qualifier brackets. These are normally SE or DE brackets that stop earlier than it's "normal" counterpart.

Qualifiers are stopped at different stages based on how many players the organizer wants to go through. Let's take an example; say you organize a tournament, and you want the best 2 players from that tournament to win entry into another tournament held at another time and place. You do not want them to play the final, they are qualified if they reach it. In CueScore, you would select a "Single Elimination 16-Q2" and run the tournament as normal. The final is not displayed as a match to be played in the bracket, and when you finish the tournament the result list will only show the "qualified" players.

*Qualifier brackets are very handy when you have a lot of players and a limited number of tables or space. By using qualifiers you can split a tournament over several sessions and avoid that all players must be in the venue all the time. This way you can e.g. have several qualifier sessions Friday and Saturday and the final on Sunday.*

### Special brackets {#special-brackets}

In the list of SE and DE brackets, you will also find some special brackets with more numbers. The extra number(s) have prefix \+.

Example: Format Double Elimination, bracket 16 \+ 8 \-16

This setup means that there will be 24 players in total, where 16 play the 1st round and 8 are seeded directly into the last 16 (SE). There are some more variations that follow the same pattern.

When selecting brackets, you will also find brackets like **DE 16 (4 x 4 groups) \- 8**.  
That is typically a Double elimination 16 \- 8, where the brackets keep the players in groups, in this case 4 groups of 4 players). This way you can easily manage sessions without all players in the venue at all times.

When you choose a bracket size, you get a link to a preview where the exact setup is shown.

# 7\. Tournament and it’s settings {#7.-tournament-and-it’s-settings}

## Create tournament {#create-tournament}

Go to the Pro dashboard and Choose “Tournaments”  
Click the “Create new” button.

![][image8]

You then have to choose between Singles tournament and Team tournament.  
Next is to confirm what Pro account is creating it (if you have access to more than one) and then it’s created when you click the “next step” button.

## Tournament settings {#tournament-settings}

Filling in the information for the tournament is pretty straight forward for most tournaments and leagues.  
Team league takes a little more input and is covered with a detailed “recipe” in the Appendix section.

### Name and date {#name-and-date}

![][image9]

***Tournament name***  
Give the league/competition a proper name and have in mind that players might do a search for it.

***Starts-Until***  
Start date/time and end date/time of the league

***Entry deadline***  
If you let teams (Captains) sign up their team themselves, this should be the last date for entry.  
If you manage the whole league and also add the teams, you can set this date back in time so that it’s not possible for others to add teams. When you work with adding teams, be sure the date is set to a future date.

***Timezone***  
Make sure it shows with local time by setting the timezone.

### Basic setup {#basic-setup}

![][image10]  
***Discipline***  
Choose the discipline to be played, e.g American Pool 10-ball.

***Race to***  
Add how many frames will be played in the match.  
If all frames are played (not race to) enter the total.  
You should inform in the description (next point) if it’s “Race to” or “Best of” a number of frames.

***“Use sets”***  
Should normally stay turned off.  
But it’s possible with a setup similar to tennis, where you have e.g 3 sets with a “Race to 7”.

***Handicap***  
If it’s a tournament where the players have a handicap to even out the differences in skills, you should activate this switch, if not leave it off.

Switching it on will give you an option to select a HCP list. This functionality will be covered in a separate point.

### Pointsystem & ranking {#pointsystem-&-ranking}

![][image11]

***Point system***  
If the tournament is part of a series or tour, you might want to create a ranking list. Then you will also need a point system to calculate points for the ranking. Here you can add a point system that has already been created. (Point system and ranking list will be covered later in this document)

***Ranking \- NEW***  
If you have created a ranking list and the tournament is part of it, you can add it in the dropdown.  
Note\! A tournament can be part of many ranking lists and you can add them one by one here (press Save for each one you add).  
You can also manage it as before from the Ranking section in the dashboard. 

### Description & participant message {#description-&-participant-message}

![][image12]  
***Description***  
Here you can add relevant information about the event. Rules, regulations…..

***Message when signing up (PREMIUM ONLY)***  
Information in this section is displayed as part of the signup procedure.  
E.g. information that the player accepts that he/she might be subject to random doping checks or similar.

### Format, size, max participants {#format,-size,-max-participants}

![][image13]

NOTE: This section varies with the type of format. For Round Robin and League brackets additional fields will appear.

***Format***  
Choose the format type you want for the tournament.  
IMPORTANT\!  
 If you organize qualifiers for a later event, make sure you use the Qualifier brackets.

***Bracket size (ref. [Format/bracket info](#6.-format-/-bracket-/-flowchart---rr/se/de))***  
Choose the correct size for your tournament.

***Max participants***  
Leave as is unless you have a limited number of players you are able to handle.

If you don’t know, you can set the max number of players you can manage and then choose the bracket size when the signups are finished.

### Ranking order for standings table {#ranking-order-for-standings-table}

\*\*\*Extra field for Round Robin and League brackets

Here you have several setups for how to sort the standings table. Priority of sorting from left to right. If Points are not part of your sorting, the next one applies (and points should be set to 0 for Win, Draw, Loss). The sorting order can be changed at any time.

On the settings page you’ll find it when scrolling about halfway down if you have chosen a Round Robin or league format. Look for this:

![][image14]  
Let us first go through the expressions:  
Points			Points awarded for a Win, Draw or Loss. You can define it yourself.  
Wins			Matches Won  
H2H			Head to head (if you and another player are even)  
Frames won		Frames won of course  
Frames lost		Frames lost to opponents  
Framescore		Frames won minus frames lost  
Innings average	Calculated (based on point score divided by no of times at the table)  
Highbreak		Best inning in point based disciplines  
Frame win average	Frames won divided by matches played

The following setups can be chosen at the time this is written:

1. Points, Wins, H2H, Frames won, Framescore, H2H  
2. Points, Wins, H2H, Innings average, Highbreak, H2H  
3. Frames won, Points, Wins, H2H, Framescore, H2H  
4. Points, Wins, Framescore, H2H, Frames won, Frames lost, H2H  
5. Points, Wins, Framescore, Frames won, H2H  
6. Points, Wins, H2H, Framescore, Frames won, Highbreak  
7. Points, Innings average, Frames won, Highbreak  
8. Points, Wins, Frames won, Framescore, H2H  
9. Frames won, H2H, Wins, Highbreak  
10. Frames won, Frame win average, Frames lost, H2H

The sorting will be done in the order they are listed.  
Example:	8\. Points, Wins, Frames won, Framescore, H2H

First we sort by highest number of points,  then number of won matches, then Frames won and so on.

***Bonus points for match winner/loser***  
If a player/team scores a certain number of frames you might want to award bonus points. That can be done for both winner or loser (if it’s a very close match).

![][image15]

The first section is “standard” point distribution. The next two are winner and loser bonus if you reach a certain number of frames/runouts/lag win.

\*\*\*The bonus point setup is usually used in combination with a fixed set of frames to be played (e.g best of 13).

Note that we have added the possibility to award a point per frame won. It can be used in combination with points for Win/Tie/Loss of the match.

# 8\. The tournament page {#8.-the-tournament-page}

This is how it looks like if you have created it (from the Pro dashboard) or have been given edit access. We’ll start with some general information and then later on go through more details and functionality.

![][image20] 

## Sections of the tournament page {#sections-of-the-tournament-page}

Depending on the status of the tournament, these are the sections of the tournament page:  
1\. Cover picture  
2\. Tournament information  
3\. Result table (if finished)  
4\. Schedule  
5\. Comments  
6\. Participant list

1\. Cover picture  
Hoover the picture with the mouse and you see a small camera appear. If you click it you can swap the default picture with your own.

2\. Tournament information  
This section displays information you added on the tournament settings page.

3\. Result table  
When the last match has been played and you click finish tournament, the result table will be created, listing players by their position.

4\. Schedule  
When all participants have joined (or you have added them), you probably want to make the draw.  
To do that, you press the “Edit” in the Schedule section and then “Create match schedule”.  
More details later.

5\. Comments  
Comments by logged in users.

6\. Participant list  
Overview of all participants that have “joined” or been added to your tournament.  
Note that you can also switch to “List view” by clicking the icon to the right.  
If you are the owner of the tournament, you will probably see some more details about the participants.

In the picture above, you find three parts marked in red.

**Settings** \- Takes you to tournament settings  
**Follow/Share** \- You can follow any tournament and also get easy access to share. If you’re the owner you can also share “Edit access” with others involved in the event (e.g tournament manager)  
**Join/Add player** \- Click Join if you want to participate. As organizer you probably also want to add other participants by using the “Add player”.

## Add player (for organizer)  {#add-player-(for-organizer)}

To improve the workflow of adding players, a new feature has been introduced.  
In the case a player profile do not exist, you can now create it directly from the tournament page. Use the “Add player” button as in picture.

![][image21]

Search for the player's name and if you don’t get a hit, create a profile for him/her with the “Create player” button.  
You will then have to input the first and last name, gender and nationality and then create the profile. It will automatically be added to your member section (Dashboard) and can be added to the tournament.

## Schedule (before draw) {#schedule-(before-draw)}

At this point you have probably added some participants to your tournament and are ready to do the draw. If not, you should probably do so. :-)

Click the “Schedule Edit” and you will see two new buttons, “Create match schedule” and “Tool” (In the picture below you see the tools menu).![][image22]

### Create match schedule {#create-match-schedule}

Before you do the actual draw, we advise you to check the tournament settings, to make sure you have the correct Format and Bracket set.

When the settings are correct, just click the button and the draw is finished within seconds.

The draw will be completely random.

### Tools {#tools}

This button gives you access to some valuable tools.

#### ***Seeding*** {#seeding}

Used to add seeding to a number of players in a tournament. This way you can make sure the top players meet as late as possible in the tournament. Very often used in bigger tournaments, to get the most exciting matches as close as possible to the final.

In the [Appendix FAQ](#appendix-2---faq) you will also find some information on how you can use Seeding to replicate a draw done “Manually” (outside of Cuescore).

#### Player swap {#player-swap}

If a player has to cancel his/hers participation in your event and you have another player that wants to join, you can use the “Player Swap” functionality.  
![][image23]  
Choose the player to be replaced from the dropdown and search for the player that will replace him/her.  
NOTE \- You can also use this if you have a free spot and get contacted by someone who wants to participate. In such a case the Player out \= Walkover.

#### Matchprotocol {#matchprotocol}

When the draw is done you can print the matchcards.

#### Reset draw {#reset-draw}

It probably doesn’t require a lot of explaining. :-)  
If you for some reason need to reset. You also have to confirm, to make sure you didn’t do this by mistake.  
You might want to check/note the seeding numbers before the reset, in case you need to get the exact same draw again.

## Schedule/bracket (when draw is done) {#schedule/bracket-(when-draw-is-done)}

![][image24]

When the draw is done, the schedule section is where you manage the tournament.

### Links and filters {#links-and-filters}

**Flowchart**  
Takes you to the “traditional” bracket view.

**Go to public view**  
If you have edit access, this will let you toggle between Edit mode and public view.

**Tools**  
Same as mentioned earlier.

**Filters \- Waiting/Playing/Finished**  
You can filter your view according to the status of your matches.  
As the tournament progresses, you might not want to see all the finished matches.

**Show walkovers**  
If you do not have a full field, the walkover matches are by default “hidden”. You can turn them on/off with the switch.

### Managing matches {#managing-matches}

The match list is where you will be most of the time when managing a tournament, so let’s go through it in detail. Starting from the left.

#### Match number and sub-menu {#match-number-and-sub-menu}

This is the match number of course, but it also has some extra functionality if you click it.

* Print match card  
* Video URL (You can add a link to the video/stream for this match). An icon will show and link to the video.  
* Add a comment (In the case you need to make a note about the match)  
* View scoreboard for streaming (Old setup, do not use it. Check “Score overlay” chapter)  
* Settings (Possibility to add Lag winner and Runout(s) if not using scoreboard)

#### Player A {#player-a}

Name of player A.  
3 dots in front of the name gives you the possibility to Forfeit/Disqualify players.

#### Expand “v” {#expand-“v”}

For some branches (Carom and Snooker) you can add Innings and Highbreak here.

#### Player B {#player-b}

Just like for player A.

#### Date / Time {#date-/-time}

Click here and you can set Date/Time for the match.  
By doing so, the players will see when their next match is planned on their “Homepage”.  
If no date/time is set, it will update when the match is started.

#### Table {#table}

If you have set a venue in the settings and it has tables registered, you can choose what table the match is to be played at.

#### Start / Finish / Edit match {#start-/-finish-/-edit-match}

Click the arrow to start the match (or start entering the result)  
Click the double arrow to finish the match.  
Click the “pause” icon to reset the match to “Not started”. Note that the scores must be 0-0. Click the arrow if you need to edit a finished match.

### Two stage tournaments, e.g. DKO-\>SKO {#two-stage-tournaments,-e.g.-dko->sko}

If you have a mixed bracket, e.g. double elimination stage leading to a single elimination stage), you will find that there is a new draw before the last stage. The draw for the last stage can be done with automatic or manual draw.

**Automatic draw** \- Random draw among the players from the loser side.

**Manual draw** \- Allows you to make the draw in your own order or starts matches as soon as you have players qualified for the last stage (to avoid waiting for all players to be finished with the first stage).

## Finish Tournament {#finish-tournament}

When all matches are finished you get access to the “Finish tournament” button just below the last match.  
When you press it, you will be able to add information related to the tournament if needed.  
Finish and then the Result table will be generated.

## Result table {#result-table}

When a tournament is finished, a result table is generated.  
If you for some reason (e.g. a player is disqualified afterhand) need to change the results, you have the option to edit the Result list.  
You can then type in the new position for players or change the points used for rankings.

# 9\. Rankings {#9.-rankings}

If you organize tours or tournaments regularly that are part of a ranking, you might make your life a lot easier by setting up the ranking in Cuescore. Set up correctly, the ranking will automatically update the moment you finish a tournament.

Use of the ranking requires that you have created a [point system](#point-systems) and added it in your tournament settings.

We advise you to start with the creation of all the tournaments that will be part of the ranking list (and the point system needed). That way you can finish up the ranking setup and kind of “forget” it. The players would probably also like to see when the tournaments take place.

![][image25]

## Settings {#settings}

**Name**  
We suggest that you give it a name that describes the ranking. E.g. “Club” summer ranking 2020

**Season**  
Choose the season it belongs to. (Start/end of season is defined in the Profile settings in the dashboard)  
The rankings are filtered by season on your “Pro page”.

**Branch**  
Select the correct branch.  
NOTE \- Only tournaments with the same branch can be added to the list.

**Counting tournaments**  
All tournaments \- Ranking position will be calculated from all included tournaments  
Best …. tournaments \- Ranking position is calculated from the best results. For example a player's best performance in 8 out of 10 tournaments.

**Description**  
Whatever information you find relevant for the ranking list.

## Ranking tournaments {#ranking-tournaments}

Click the “Tournaments” framed in red in the picture above), search the tournament name and add. (X) to remove tournaments.

# 10\. Handicap feature {#10.-handicap-feature}

A lot of tournaments make use of player handicaps to even out the playing field and make it possible for anyone to win an event, regardless of their skill level. There are different handicap systems in use around the world, and we've taken that into consideration in this first version of the feature. 

## Getting started {#getting-started}

Go to the menu option "Handicaps" in the Pro dashboard and create a new handicap list from there.

**Type** \- Please choose the type of HCP, as we want to learn a bit more about the most commonly used ones, for future improvements.

Once you've created the list, you can add players to it and set their handicap. Actually, you do not have to add players to the list itself, as players are added to it automatically when entering your tournament. You will have to set their actual handicap though, so it is advisable to add all your regular players straight away.

To make use of a handicap list in a tournament, first create your tournament. From the "Handicap" section of the tournament edit page you turn on using handicaps, and you will get a selection box from which you can select the handicap list you just created.

## Editing handicaps {#editing-handicaps}

You can edit handicap levels in two places.

Using the handicap list you just created will alter the current handicap level of any player, and is considered the "maintenance" area. Whenever you need to update the current handicap level of a player you should do that from there.

The second place to edit a handicap is through the playing schedule of a tournament. In the schedule, next to the player name in every match you will find a three dotted menu item, which will bring up a small menu. In that list you will find "Edit handicap" and by clicking that you can edit that player's handicap directly. Changing the handicap from here will also update the handicap list (the current handicap level), unless you check "Update only this match".

![][image26]

# 12\. Score overlay for streaming {#12.-score-overlay-for-streaming}

The score overlay feature is a very popular functionality. With only some basic knowledge about streaming you can get started offering a professional look to your streams.

The only thing required is that you use a streaming software where you can add a browser source that supports transparency in web pages. We recommend using the free streaming application [OBS Studio](https://obsproject.com/),  more about that later. 

Before explaining how you can start using it, here's a working example from a Norwegian tournament at Oslo Biljardsenter \- [Score overlay](https://youtu.be/UC4UqAfBHGI?t=487)

*In the example the scoreboard overlay coupled with scoreboard tablets at the venue*

## How to get going {#how-to-get-going}

Every venue/playing facility registered in our database has a certain number of tables installed. Those tables get their own ID in our database, and by providing us with that table ID, we can provide you with the correct match happening at the table at any given time. This means that once you've added the overlay to your stream, you can just leave it. No need to update whenever a new match is on, the overlay always knows when a match is on or not.

## 12.1 Get the table link {#12.1-get-the-table-link}

First of all, you need to get the correct table ID for the table you want to provide streaming for. Go to Venues in the Pro dashboard hosting the tournament, click the venue you are using for the tournament and then the “Billiard tables” tab. Look up the table you will be streaming from and copy the link (blue text) below “Streaming overlay”.

You can also find the link on the venue page itself. Search for the venue name and click the link. Once on the venue's page, (f.ex: [Oslo Biljardsenter](https://cuescore.com/place/Oslo+Biljardsenter/1000328) ) you will see the "Billiard tables" available at the venue.

In the list of billiard tables you'll see the table number, table size, manufacturer and so on. One of the columns in that table has a header that says "Scoreboard overlay". Copy the link in that column to get the correct link for your table.

## 12.2 Add a browser source in your streaming software {#12.2-add-a-browser-source-in-your-streaming-software}

We recommend using the free streaming application [OBS Studio](https://obsproject.com/) (Open Broadcaster Software) when doing your live streams. Other software is fine too as long as the browser source extension supports transparency in web pages.

When setting up the scoreboard overlay you need to add it to the "sources" list as a "browser" source. Open the dialog to add it, paste the link from step one, then set the preferred size of the webpage. This last step is important as it will define how big/small the overlay will appear on the resulting video. If you plan to broadcast in full HD, you should set the width and height of the browser source to 1920x1080 pixels. For 720p you enter 1280x720 and so on. The overlay is intended to cover the whole area of your video source, so be sure to enter values that correspond to the video output size. You can of course mix and match this as you see fit, but you should know what size you are streaming (sending to youtube or whatever) and keep it the same size for the best result.

![][image27]

*Adding a browser source in OBS Studio*

 

## 12.3 How it works (and when) {#12.3-how-it-works-(and-when)}

If you've set this up properly you should see tournament and match information (see example image) in OBS now. If not, the tournament or match might not have started or been created yet. Make sure the tournament exists and that the match you want to stream is set up to use the same table as you've just set up in the streaming software. Important things to check if nothing comes up is the dates of the tournament, the status of the match (must be "playing" (blue)), and that the correct table number has been selected for it.

If you can see tournament information, but not the match you were anticipating, don't worry. The match will not be visible until it actually starts. The scoreboard overlay keeps track of this by itself, and will show the match scoreboard once the match has been started by the tournament manager.

Once the match is finished, the match scoreboard will disappear (fade out) and only the tournament information will be shown (top left). At this time (between matches) you can expect to see results from other matches, info about what is the next match and so on, based on what the tournament manager enters into the system. More on this later as this is currently under development.

## 12.4 What information is shown {#12.4-what-information-is-shown}

We include a bit more information than we had on the previous scoreboard, and the content is divided into two main sections. The top left section, and the center bottom section.

In the top left section you'll find:

* Logo of the organizer (or CueScore logo for private tournaments)  
* Tournament date (from \- to)  
* Tournament name  
* Venue name  
* Discipline

In the center bottom section (the actual scoreboard), you'll find:

* Player A and B names  
* Profile images of both players, and their nationality flag  
* Score player A and B (well, duh..)  
* Table number  
* Race to length  
* Round  
* Innings and average for both players for disciplines where this is relevant

Both sections also include the color selected as the main color for the organization if selected (if not, it will be a grey gradient).

## 12.5 Language support {#12.5-language-support}

You can get the scoreboard in any of the languages we currently support. The default language is english, and to override the language you'll have to add a "lang=" parameter to the URL (from step 1).

This is the scoreboard URL for table 1 at CueScore headquarters:

[https://cuescore.com/scoreboard/overlay/?tableId=1167880](https://cuescore.com/scoreboard/overlay/?tableId=1167880)

To get the scoreboard in Norwegian, I'll have to add the parameter mentioned, like this:

[https://cuescore.com/scoreboard/overlay/?tableId=1167880\&lang=nb](https://cuescore.com/scoreboard/overlay/?tableId=1167880&lang=nb)

For your convenience, here's a list of codes for languages we support as of today. Replace "nb" with the code for your language in the scoreboard URL:

| Code | Language |
| :---- | :---- |
| en | English |
| nb | Norwegian Bokmål |
| fr | French |
| el | Greek |
| de | German |
| nl | Dutch |
| mk | North Macedonian |
| fi | Finnish |
| es | Spanish |
| sq | Albanian |
| ru | Russian |
| se | Swedish |
| pl | Polish |
| it | Italian |
| pt | Brazilian portuguese |
| hr | Croatian |
| sk | Slovak |
| ja | Japanese |
| da | Danish |
| zh | Chinese |

 

## 12.6 What's next? {#12.6-what's-next?}

General improvements of the workflow.

The scoreboard overlay has some cool features planned. Connected with the scoreboard for tablets application, we will have the ability to show statistical information about the match in between frames or after the match, we can show results from other matches appearing in the overlay at certain times (when other matches finish f.ex).

# APPENDIX 1 \- Team league setup {#appendix-1---team-league-setup}

This is a Step-by-step guide and you will probably recognise parts of it from earlier in the document. 

Following this guide will minimize the need for jumping back and forth within Cuescore, and it probably starts with something different from what you expect. :-)

## 1\. Teams home-venue {#1.-teams-home-venue}

If the teams have a home venue, this is where we start.  
Check that the venues are registered in Cuescore. If not, add them.

## 2\. Players on the team {#2.-players-on-the-team}

If you are one of the early users of Cuescore in your country a lot of the players might not have a profile in Cuescore. Then it will be a good start to go through your list of players on the teams, to check if all the players have a Cuescore profile.

Go to your PRO dashboard and click the “Members” section.  
![][image28]

Press the “Add” button and you will get a dialogue box where you can both search to see if there is an existing profile of the player and create one if there isn’t.

Go through your list of players and do a search for their name. 

If there is no profile, click the “New member” and add at least Name, Gender, Nationality and Country.  
Profiles created this way (for PRO’s only) will be public profiles and duplicate problems will be minimized.

## 3\. Now it’s time to create the teams {#3.-now-it’s-time-to-create-the-teams}

Go to the Manager section on your login-page a (click the Cuescore logo and then “Manager”)   
In the menu to the left you, click “Teams”.  
If you have never created teams before, this section will be empty. If you have created teams, this is the fastest way to find them if you need to edit.

At the right, you see a button “Add team”. Next step is probably logical….click it.

![][image29]

Fill in Team name and add description (optional).

*Represents (Optional)*  
If the team is representing an organization that has a Cuescore PRO, start typing the name and choose it. If the team is not connected to a PRO, leave it empty.

*My venue (optional)*  
Now you see why we did point 1\. Add the team's home venue if it has one.

*Preferred weekday & time (Optional)*  
To make the time planning very smooth. We have added the possibility to set a team’s preferred weekday & time. After the draw is done, you can add the week number per round and this information can be added automatically per round.

There are at least three different cases:

1. All team rounds and matches are played the same week, weekday and time.  
   If so, add the same weekday and time for all teams.  
2. Matches are played on the preferred weekday and time of the Home-team.  
   Add the different teams’ preferred weekday and time  
3. Rounds and matches are planned in other ways  
   If this is the case, leave the fields empty. Time/date will have to be added per match.

*Add the players to their team*  
When the team info has been added, add the team members.  
This should be very smooth, as we checked and created the member profiles in point 2\.

Important\! Usually a team has a captain. The captain can be set by clicking the star in front of his name. By doing this, the captain will have extra privileges like editing the team and entering individual scores for his team.

Repeat for all the teams in the league.

## 4\. Create league / Competition {#4.-create-league-/-competition}

So, finally we have reached the part where we actually create the league/competition.

1. At this point you are probably at the Manager section of your Cuescore login page and you have two options:  
   Click the arrow down beside your profile picture and select the PRO. Choose “Tournaments” and “Create new”.  
     
2. Or you can use the faster way and just click tournaments on your Manager page and then “Create new”.

Complete the following steps:

1. In the popup choose “Team tournament” and next.  
2. You probably want to create it from your PRO account, so choose the PRO name as organizer, not your personal account.  
3. Press next and the Tournament is created.

**It’s time to fill in League data**  
Most of the setup is very straightforward, but we will go through it step-by-step anyway.  
![][image30]

**Name and date**  
*Tournament name*  
Give the league/competition a proper name and have in mind that players might do a search for it.

*Starts-Until*  
Start date/time and end date/time of the league

*Entry deadline*  
If you let teams (Captains) sign up their team themselves, this should be the last date for entry.  
If you manage the whole league and also add the teams, you can set this date back in time so that it’s not possible for others to add teams. When you work with adding teams, be sure the date is set to a future date.

*Timezone*  
Make sure it shows with local time by setting the timezone.

**Basic setup**  
*Discipline*  
Choose the discipline to be played in the league (Multiball can be used in the case there are several disciplines played in American pool)

*Race to*  
Add how many frames will be played per team match.  
If all frames are played (not race to) enter the total.

*“Use sets”*  
Should normally stay turned off.

*Point system*  
Leave as is. Not used for leagues as they have their own standings table and point settings.

*Handicap*  
Leave off normally

**Description & participant message**  
*Description*  
Here you can add relevant information about the League. Rules, regulations…..

*Message when signing up (PREMIUM ONLY)*  
If you do a setup where the teams have to sign up themselves, you can add a message the is displayed as part of the signup procedure. It could be that you have some important information you want every team to notice.

**Format, size, max participants**  
![][image31]  
*Format*  
Choose “League”

*Bracket size*  
You have several different League setups, where the 2x, 3x…..tells you how many times the teams will meet up. If the league has few teams, you might want them to meet 3-4 times. If there are many teams it might be enough with 2x to fill the season with a weekly match.

Ex. League 2x \- all teams play each other twice. Once at the home venue and once at the opponent's venue.

*Max participants*  
Leave as is unless you have a limitation like max 10 teams.

*Ranking order for standings*  
Here you have several setups for how to sort the standings table. Priority of sorting from left to right. If Points are not part of your sorting, the next one applies (and points should be set to 0 for Win, Draw, Loss).

*Bonus points for match winner/loser*  
If a team scores a certain number of frames you might want to award bonus points. That can be done for both the winner or loser (if it’s a very close match).

**Template for individual matches**

**![][image32]**

Here you can add the individual matches you use for the Team match. When the draw is done, all team matches will have the liste individual matches added.

**Switches**

1. “Disable all match setup changes………..”  
   As you can give the team captains access to add scores for the individual matches, you have an option here to block them for changing the type of matches, discipline and race to.

2. “Use playing sequence”  
   If you are a first time user/test, you can probably leave this off.

   This is a tool where the team captains can choose a number of players for each match (usually 3 or 5\) that will meet the opponents players in a fixed order.  
   Often used in Blackball with 1 frame matches.  
   More info is found in a separate point later in the document. See [Use playing sequence](#6.-player-sequence-individual-matches)

**Organizers**  
*![][image17]*

*Organizer*  
If the league is created by a PRO user, the name of the PRO is already here. 

*Tournament manager*  
Add the tournament manager(s). Contact info will be shown for these persons.  
Note that this does not give them access to edit the tournament.  
\*\*\*Access to edit is done with the “Share” button in the top section of the tournament/league.

*Venue*  
If the whole league is played in one venue only, add it here. If teams have a home venue set, you do not need to add a venue here.

The switch “Make team venues accessible in the schedule” will allow for automatically setting the venue based on the information added on the team (home venue) and makes it possible to change it for each team match.

**Age, gender & dress code**  
![][image18]  
*Age restriction*  
Only to be used if you are sure all players have their age set correctly. (Usually Premium users)

*Gender*  
Can be used to define Men or Women only tournaments.

*onlyDresscode*  
Activates only as an info text for the tournament/league.

**Video / live stream**  
*![][image19]*

*Add stream/video*  
You can add a stream link or link to a video from the event, that will show on the tournament/League page.

**Pay\&Play Entry fee**  
Some countries have the option to activate Cuescore Pay\&Play functionality.  
If activated, you can set the price for signup and let the teams pay League entry online as part of the signup process.

**Delete / Publish / Save draft**  
Then we have reached the end of the setup and the League can be created.  
Delete \- Self explanatory  
Publish \- Publish the tournament  
Save draft \- Keep it in draft if you didn’t finish the settings

As we now want to add teams, we press “Publish”.

## 5\. Add teams and make the draw {#5.-add-teams-and-make-the-draw}

Once you published the league, you were sent to the league page.  
Now you can add the teams you created earlier. Use the button to the right.

![][image33]

* Search the team names and add them one by one. As soon as the teams are added, it’s time to do the draw.  
    
* Scroll to the “Schedule” section and press “Create match schedule”.  
  **IMPORTANT\!** If you have conflicting matches, see point 7 below before you make the draw.

Cuescore will now create all the Rounds, Team matches and Individual matches within seconds.

* You can now set the date/time for each team match.  
* Add players to individual matches (if you are in charge)  
* Start matches and enter scores  
* …..

**Standings table**  
As soon as a match is finished, the standings table is updated.

## 6\. Player sequence individual matches {#6.-player-sequence-individual-matches}

This functionality is especially developed for English pool/Blackball team league events, but can probably be of interest for other disciplines as well.  
For each team match the captains choose the 3,4,5,6,7,9,11 or 15 players to play the individual matches and they will meet the opponents in a fixed order (playing sequence).  
Before the team match starts, both teams captains (or the organizer) choose the defined number of players from their team assigned as number 1-3 or 1-5.  
When both captains have done so, the draw for the individual matches is automatically done and the players will be matched up as shown when you press the “Autofill Sequence columns” button. (or you can define your own sequence/rotation of players)

**IMPORTANT\!** Access to set player sequence becomes available for Captains at the planned date of the match.

Example  
Team league, with 3 players from each team and 9 individual matches (3 for each of the players). Settings:  
![][image34]

As you might have figured out, the 3 first matchups will be as follows:

Match 1	Player no **1** from team A \- Player no **1** from team B  
Match 2	Player no **2** from team A \- Player no **2** from team B  
Match 3	Player no **3** from team A \- Player no **3** from team B

Match 4	Player no **2** from team A \- Player no **3** from team B  
Match 5	Player no **3** from team A \- Player no **1** from team B  
and you have probably understood it by now…...

**How to set player 1, 2 and 3?**  
With the use of Team Captains (defined in the team settings), each of the two captains will now have access to choose the players in the order they want.

When the Captain opens the team match (press the “Arrow down” ) he/she gets access to a button for his team “Set playing sequence A” (for the Captain on the team to the left). Click it and it will look like in the picture below.  
Choose player no 1-3 and save.  
When both captains have done so, the individual matches will be drawn with the player corresponding to the number in the playing sequence setup.

![][image35]

For the next team match the procedure is repeated by the team captains.  
**\*\*\*** Note that the league manager has access to set the player sequence for both teams.

## 7\. Conflicting matches {#7.-conflicting-matches}

It’s not uncommon that several teams have the same home-venue. When setting up a league you might want to make a setup where the teams do not play at home the same day , except for the match(es) where they play each other. The most common reason for this type of setup is if the venue has just a few pool tables.

If you know this is a problem for your league, you can use the seeding numbers to make sure one team plays away when the other team plays at home.

Planning for this is quite simple, by looking at the league brackets.

1. Make a note of the teams that have the same home venue  
2. Go to the Cuescore brackets page ([League brackets](https://cuescore.com/schema/?s=1000&p=8&Send=Submit+Query)), choose the league type and enter the number of teams that participate in your league.  
   In round 1 you see the seeding numbers and this is what we are going to use.  
3. For the two teams with the same venue, add the Top left seeding to one team and lower right seeding to the other team.  
4. If you have more teams with a conflict, repeat the process but use the second number from top / bottom.  
5. Make a note of the needed seeding numbers and open the Seeding option on your league page.  
6. Add the seeding number pairs you wrote down in point 3\.  
7. When all possible conflicts have been taken care of, close the seeding and create the match schedule.

**Example:**  
You want to run a League 1x with 8 teams participating.Two teams have the same home venue and can not play a home match on the same day. In the [brackets section](https://cuescore.com/schema/?s=1000&Send=Send) I find the following setup:

![][image36]  
Before I make a draw, I need to add seeding numbers to the two teams.  
From the picture above I see that I need to use one of the seeding numbers pairs, 1-4, 2-6, 3-7 or 5-8 for these teams.  
I open the seeding functionality (tools Icon when in edit mode for the league) and add  seeding numbers to the two teams, 1 to one team and 4 to the other team.  
Then I can make the draw and be sure the teams do not play at home the same day.

# APPENDIX 2 \- FAQ {#appendix-2---faq}

**Login problems**  
If you just created your profile, make sure to check your email for the confirmation link sent to it. Remember to also check your spam folder.

For any other problems, contact us at [support@cuescore.com](mailto:support@cuescore.com). Include the link to your profile.

**Duplicate profiles**  
If you find more than one profile of yourself, make a claim for it and use the same email as you used to register your “official” profile. We will then merge them during weekdays.

**Claim profile**  
If you are new to the platform, you might find that a tournament organizer has created a profile for you. To activate it with a login, simply use the “Claim profile” link and follow the instructions.  
If the person that created the profile also added your email, the claim will be handled automatically. If it was not registered, we will usually handle the claim within 24 hours during workdays.

**Forfeit / Disqualify (FF/DIS)**  
When in edit mode of the tournament you will find these options “behind” the three dots to the left of the players’ name.  
FF \- Usually used if a player doesn’t show for his/her match (or too late)  
DIS \- Used if the player doesn’t show up at all, if regulations are not followed or if it is the second match where the player shows up too late.

NOTE \- For leagues and Round Robin formats, a FF is automatically changed to DIS, to make sure the standings table is fair.

**Brackets/Schema**  
If you go to the [schema/brackets](https://cuescore.com/schema/) page you can preview all brackets. If the schema type has a flowchart, you are also able to view that.

**Replicate a draw from “outside” of Cuescore**  
If you for some reason have done the draw “outside” of Cuescore and want to get the same matchups, follow this procedure:

1. Look up the bracket you want to use on the schema page (link in point above).  
   For each match you see the seeding number for Player A and B.  
2. Add the seeding numbers according to your draw. ([Tools button](#seeding))  
3. Make the draw (Create match schedule).

# APPENDIX 3 \- Tips & tricks {#appendix-3---tips-&-tricks}

## Copy tournament {#copy-tournament}

If you organize weekly tournaments with the same settings, you might save some time by using the “Copy tournament” functionality.  
Go to the Dashboard and select “Tournaments”. Look up the one you want to copy and click the “Copy” icon.  
Remember to edit the name and check the start date.

Participants are not part of the copy function (at least not yet).

## Replicating a tournament (managed in another system) {#replicating-a-tournament-(managed-in-another-system)}

If you want to replicate a tournament that you did outside CueScore, then you have to use seeding for all players in the competition to replicate the original draw.

Let's use 2012 World Pool Masters as example:

1. You have the original draw [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012\_World\_Pool\_Masters](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_World_Pool_Masters)  
2. Then in CueScore before creating match schedule, you have to go to Seeding first and for each player (not only the seeded Top8) you need to assign the position in the brackets:

   1 Ralf Souquet  
   16 Mateusz Śniegocki  
   …  
   7 SvB  
   10 Karol Skowerski

   15 Tony Drago  
   2 Darren Appleton

3. Then, when all players are assigned as in original according to a particular bracket type, you can create schedule and replicate the results. In case of 2010 WPM it would be according to this: [https://cuescore.com/tournament/bracket/?schematype=104](https://cuescore.com/tournament/bracket/?schematype=104)

\*\*\* Note that to replicate a double elimination tournament it has to be the same crossing from winner to loser side.
